04085nam a22005415i 9780773586765DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735867657 a10.1515/97807735867652doi  a(DE-B1597)655000  a(OCoLC)884955402  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR3316.A4bZ464 1988 v.5 7aBIO0220002bisacsh04a828/.603aB22004aThe Early Journals and Letters of Fanny Burney: Volume V, 1782-1783 :bVolume V, 1782-1783 /ced. by Stewart J. Cooke, Lars E. Troide. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (528 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tShort Titles and Abbreviations -- tEarly Journals and Letters of Fanny Burney -- tUndated Items From 1783 -- tFanny Burney’s Meeting With Mary Delany -- tElizabeth Meeke’s Letter to Fanny Burney -- tFanny Burney’s Second Letter to Hester Lynch Thrale on 20 July 1781 -- tEvelina in Mr Villars’ Study -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVolume V of The Early Journals and Letters of Fanny Burney covers a period of significant gains and losses for the young writer. Professionally, Burney consolidated her reputation as England's premier novelist with the publication of Cecilia. Through a mutual friendship she gained an appointment as Keeper of the Robes to Queen Charlotte, a position that provided both financial security and an insider's view to life at Court. Burney's professional success during these years was balanced by countless personal setbacks. Deprived of the companionship of her favourite sister following her sister's marriage, she also lost the friendship of Hester Lynch Thrale who grew increasingly distant during her romantic attachment to Gabriel Piozzi (whom she married in 1784). The death of her dear friend and mentor Samuel Crisp causes Burney deep sadness, and her emotional turmoil is further exacerbated by her introduction to George Owen Cambridge, a young clergyman to whom she is clearly attracted but who refuses to either declare himself to her, or leave her in peace. Throughout these trials and triumphs, Burney - an artist with an acute sense of the complexities and vagaries of human nature - never ceases to fix her lens on the fashions and follies of English society as they emerge in the manners of her time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNovelists, Englishy18th centuryvCorrespondence. 0aNovelists, Englishy18th centuryvDiaries. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh1 aCooke, Stewart J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTroide, Lars E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358676540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773586765423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773586765/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles